ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
(a) Water flux (Jw
                     ), reverse salt flux (Js
                     ) and (b) specific reverse salt flux (Js
                     /Jw
                     ) of the blank TFC and modified TFN-MAsx membranes with various MIL-53-NH-Asp loading in FO and PRO modes (under 1 M NaCl as the DS and DI water as the FS); (c) FO performance of the control TFC and the optimal TFN-MAs3 (with 0.09 wt% NPs loading) membranes at different DS concentrations (0.5 – 2.0 M) under FO orientation.

ce:section.ce:para:
The fouling test of the blank TFC membrane and optimal TFN-MAs3 membrane was conducted in the presence of sodium alginate (SA) and bovine serum albumin (BSA) as a model organic and protein foulant under FO orientation. To begin with, at the first step, DI water is circulated in both faces of the membrane for half an hour to clean the system and afterward is replaced with fresh DI water and NaCl solution (0.5 – 1.5 M) so as to regulate the water flux to an approximate value of 20 MLH – roughly constant – by adjusting the DS concentration (Jw,0
                        ). Progressively, FS is supplanted with synthetic wastewater (containing various mono- and divalent ions) free from any foulant to achieve baseline water flux (J0
                        ) and alleviate the dropped water flux caused by DS dilution coupled with salt penetration to FS [46,49]. This very process has been repeated distinctively in the presence of SBA and SA (with 250 ppm concentration in synthetic wastewater solution), so fouling could take place, yielding dynamic water flux (Jt
                        ). To draw a comparative conclusion about the anti-fouling performance of membranes, a graph of normalized water flux versus time has been devised by dividing values of Jt
                         to J0
                        . Moreover, to evaluate the reversibility of the membrane fouling phenomenon, a physical rinsing method was carried out without any chemical agents. This course of action has been conducted by exchanging feed and draw solutions with DI water and increasing the circulation rate two times faster than normal condition (400 ml/min), lasting for half an hour; water flux recovery value has been obtained under a condition similar to baseline.
